  <h2>Sonuç</h2>
  <p>Japonya'nın deneyiminin en önemli mesajı şudur: <strong>depreme hazırlık bir proje değil, bir kültürdür</strong>. Teknoloji önemlidir, yapı standartları kritiktir; ancak bunların tamamını ayakta tutan, hazırlığı günlük yaşamın ayrılmaz parçası olarak gören toplumsal bilinçtir. Türkiye bu bilinci inşa etme yolundadır; 1999 ve 2023 depremlerinin ardından farkındalık büyümüştür. Şimdi bu farkındalığı kalıcı eyleme dönüştürme zamanıdır.</p>

  <Fragment slot="en">
  <p>Japan is one of the world's most seismically active countries. Approximately <strong>20% of the world's M6.0+ earthquakes occur in Japan</strong>, and the country must cope with more than 1,500 felt tremors every year. More than 15,000 people lost their lives in the tsunami that followed the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake — yet that disaster also demonstrated how robust the country's infrastructure had become. Had the same earthquake struck elsewhere, the casualties could have been far greater.</p>

  <p>Japan's earthquake preparedness system has been built over decades, tested repeatedly, and continuously refined. In this article we explore the core components of that system and the concrete lessons Turkey — and the world — can draw from Japan's experience.</p>

  <div class="stat-band">
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-num">~20%</span><span class="stat-label">of the world's M6+ earthquakes occur in Japan</span></div>
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-num">1,500+</span><span class="stat-label">felt earthquakes in Japan per year</span></div>
    <div class="stat"><span class="stat-num">80 sec</span><span class="stat-label">early warning lead time from P-wave detection to 2011 Tōhoku tsunami</span></div>
  </div>

  <h2>1. Early Warning System: Seconds Save Lives</h2>
  <p>Japan operates the world's most advanced earthquake early warning system, run by the <strong>Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA)</strong> through a network of more than 4,000 seismic sensors. The moment sensors detect a P-wave (the faster, less destructive first wave), an alert is broadcast nationally — giving people seconds to take cover before the destructive S-wave arrives.</p>
  <p>This alert reaches smartphones, TV and radio broadcasts, railway systems, factories, and schools simultaneously. Shinkansen bullet trains brake automatically before shaking begins; surgical operations are halted; elevators move to the nearest floor and open their doors.</p>

  <h2>2. Building Standards: Codes Updated After Every Earthquake</h2>
  <p>Japan revises its building regulations after every major earthquake. The landmark 1981 reform (<em>Shin-taishin</em>) is the pivot point of the system: the difference in damage between buildings constructed before and after 1981 is striking in every subsequent major earthquake.</p>

  <div class="vis-grid">
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 9l9-7 9 7v11a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2z"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Mandatory Retrofitting</h3>
      <p>Pre-1981 public buildings, schools, and hospitals were required to be retrofitted; most have been completed. Subsidy schemes also incentivise private building owners.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"/><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5-10-5-10 5z"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Seismic Isolation</h3>
      <p>Critical structures — hospitals, data centres, government buildings — use seismic isolation systems so that while the building sways, the occupants and equipment inside remain virtually stationary.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="2" y="7" width="20" height="14" rx="2"/><path d="M16 7V5a2 2 0 0 0-2-2h-4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v2"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Wooden Housing Transition</h3>
      <p>Japan's traditional wooden structures carry fire and collapse risk; urban renewal programmes are converting them to modern buildings — a process still ongoing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="vis-card">
      <div class="vis-card-icon"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M22 12h-4l-3 9L9 3l-3 9H2"/></svg></div>
      <h3>Transparent Damage Database</h3>
      <p>Detailed damage analyses are published after every earthquake. Which building types failed and why is fed directly into the next revision of the code.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>3. Cultural Preparedness: Readiness Is Part of Daily Life</h2>
  <p>Japan's greatest advantage is not technology or budget — it is <strong>cultural preparedness</strong>. Earthquake readiness is woven into the education system, the workplace, and family life:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>1 September every year:</strong> Observed as "Disaster Prevention Day." Drills are conducted nationwide; the date marks the anniversary of the 1923 Great Kantō Earthquake and keeps preparedness awareness alive.</li>
    <li><strong>School curriculum:</strong> Earthquake safety is an integral part of the curriculum from primary school onwards. Children participate in drills several times a year.</li>
    <li><strong>Workplace drills:</strong> Companies are legally obliged to conduct regular drills and maintain emergency supply stocks.</li>
    <li><strong>Neighbourhood solidarity:</strong> Every neighbourhood has a disaster coordinator; residents are aware of each other's safety situation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4. Tsunami Preparedness: Vertical Evacuation</h2>
  <p>One of the most painful lessons of the 2011 Tōhoku tsunami was that horizontal evacuation routes are sometimes not enough. Japan responded by building <strong>vertical evacuation structures</strong> in coastal towns — specially designed multi-storey platforms that remain above tsunami flood levels. Some existing buildings have also had their rooftops reinforced and designated as evacuation points.</p>
  <p>Turkey's Aegean, Marmara, and Mediterranean coastlines carry tsunami risk. For residents of these areas, identifying a <strong>high ground location within walking distance</strong> before any warning is issued is critically important.</p>

  <h2>What Turkey Can Do: Concrete Takeaways</h2>
  <p>Japan's system was built over decades and with substantial resources. Turkey cannot reach the same point overnight — but there are actionable lessons at the individual, community, and policy levels:</p>

  <div class="roadmap">
    <div class="roadmap-step">
      <div class="roadmap-marker">
